article.description:
Jerry Stackhouse had 24 points and 11 assists, and
three players scored 16 points each as the Detroit Pistons beat the
Denver Nuggets 98-91 Monday night.
article.headline: Pistons increase lead over Bucks, defeat Nuggets
article.linkText: Pistons blow lead, bounce back to beat Nuggets
article.story:
DENVER (AP) -- The Detroit Pistons lost all of an 18-point lead to one of the worst teams in the league. Jerry Stackhouse didn't let them lose the game. Stackhouse had 24 points and 11 assists, and led a fourth-quarter surge that sent the Pistons over the Denver Nuggets 98-91 Monday night. "I thought I was in a pretty good rhythm tonight, and I felt the best that I've felt in a long time this morning," said Stackhouse, who has been bothered by shoulder and hip injuries. "I was happily surprised this morning with the way I felt when I got up. It showed tonight because I was able to hit some shots." Detroit led by as much 18 points in the first half, but the Nuggets got eight straight points from Voshon Lenard to pull within 82-81 with 6:52 left. The Nuggets took their first lead 43 seconds later when Donnell Harvey dunked over Corliss Williamson. But Stackhouse came back with a 3-pointer and a baseline jumper to put Detroit ahead 89-83. Stackhouse, who was 4-for-7 from 3-point range, also held Lenard scoreless over the final 6:52. "Lenard was getting it done and I think Stack wanted a chance at him," Pistons coach Rick Carlisle said. "He stopped Lenard two or three straight times and that was huge because he was in one of those grooves where he was hitting a lot of difficult shots." Detroit moved two games ahead of Milwaukee for the Central Division lead and within 3½ games of idle New Jersey for the top spot in the Eastern Conference. Denver lost its fifth straight. The Nuggets shot 50 percent for just the sixth time this season, but are 0-for-11 from 3-point range the last two games after making at least one in 255 straight. Denver also had 18 turnovers, including two on shot-clock violations in the fourth quarter. "It is a sign of a lack of focus," Nuggets coach Mike Evans said. "You see that when you are consistently getting called for shot-clock violations in the last three minutes of games. We have to do a better job of executing our offense down the stretch." Williamson, Cliff Robinson and Chucky Atkins each had 16 points for the Pistons. Ben Wallace scored six of his 11 points on alley-oop dunks, and also had 15 rebounds. Lenard and Juwan Howard scored 18 points for Denver. Carlos Arroyo, making his first career start, had six points and eight assists for the Nuggets. He replaced Tim Hardaway, who finished out serving a two-game suspension for throwing a television onto the court Friday against Orlando. The Nuggets struggled early in a 101-76 loss to Miami on Saturday, and got off to another slow start against Detroit. Denver had turnovers on four of its first seven possessions, had two of its first three shots blocked and scored just two points in the first 5:02. Detroit was 13-for-24 from the floor and led 34-18 after one quarter. "The defense wasn't there. We allowed Detroit to score at will," Howard said. "When you allow a team to score 34 points in the first quarter, you make you job harder. We have to prevent that." The Nuggets chipped their 18-point deficit to 50-44 on an 18-foot jumper by George McCloud with 2:38 left in the second quarter, but Stackhouse hit a 3-pointer and Atkins scored on a scoop shot to put the Pistons back up by 11. The Nuggets got within 3 when Arroyo hit a jumper at the shot-clock buzzer, but Detroit came back with seven straight points to push the lead to 71-61 with 4:25 left in the third quarter. Detroit blocked eight shots in the first half and had nine total. Game notes
NBA commissioner David Stern, who attended the game, was mildly booed when introduced in the first quarter and had to combat Frisbee dogs during a halftime television interview. ... Detroit won just its second game in 11 tries against the Western Conference. ... Detroit's Zeljko Rebraca wore a clear mask to protect his broken right orbital bone. ... Denver had scored at least 100 points in five of eight games Antonio McDyess started.
